ariants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger de Braham was born about 1260, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of William de Braham. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1286, in his hometown, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1260–1286":"umbes 1260–1286","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1260–1286":"noin 1260–1286","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","about 1260":"noin 1260","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1260–1286":"environ 1260–1286","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","about 1260":"environ 1260","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Rog